{{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | name = Noto Province General Shrine | image = [[File:能登国総社.jpg|300px]] | location = Furumachi Ki, Nanao City, Ishikawa Prefecture, Japan | coordinates = {{Coord|37|1|21|N|136|54|59|E|region:JP-17_type:landmark_scale:10000|display=inline,title}} | deity = Forty-three deities of Noto Province | status = | founded = | hondo = | othernames = | festivals = | rituals = | map = Japan Ishikawa }}
The '''Noto Province General Shrine''' ({{lang|ja|総社}}, {{lang|ja|能登国総社}}, Sōsha, Noto-koku Sōja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en}} located in {{ill|Nanao|ja|七尾市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan. It served as the {{ill|Sōja|ja|総社|12=draft|12=draft}} (General Shrine) of {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|12=draft|12=draft}} and is designated as a municipal-level {{ill|Tangible Cultural Property|ja|有形文化財|12=draft|12=draft}}.
=== History === The shrine is located 800 meters southeast of the {{ill|Historic Site|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan|12=draft|12=draft}}} of the {{ill|Noto Kokubun-ji|ja|能登国分寺|12=draft|12=draft}} ruins, at the tip of a hill. To the east of the shrine flows the Ōtani River, which once served as a natural moat for {{ill|Nanao Castle|ja|七尾城|12=draft|12=draft}}. The shrine enshrines the deities of the forty-three {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}} of Noto Province.
The origins of the Sōja system date back to the mid- to late-{{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, when provincial governors ({{ill|Kokushi|ja|国司|12=draft|12=draft}}) consolidated the deities of local shrines at a single location near the provincial office ({{ill|Kokuga|ja|国衙|12=draft|12=draft}}) for convenience in rituals and offerings. According to shrine tradition, the shrine initially enshrined Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto. Later, {{ill|Minamoto no Shitagō|ja|源順|12=draft|12=draft}}, while serving as Governor of Noto, rebuilt the shrine and enshrined the forty-three Shikinaisha deities of Noto.
=== Designated Cultural Properties === ==== Sōja Honden (main hall) ==== The main hall, built in the {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|12=draft|12=draft}} architectural style with a cypress-bark roof, is a small, front-facing structure located within a protective covering that connects to the worship hall. Built in {{nihongo|1637|寛永14th year }}, a roof inscription reveals that the hall was reoriented southward in {{nihongo|1674|延宝2nd year }}.
==== Sōja Thirty-Six Immortals of Poetry Panels (Thirty-Six Pieces) ==== The set comprises thirty-six framed panels, each depicting one of the {{ill|Thirty-Six Immortals of Poetry|ja|三十六歌仙|12=draft|12=draft}}. The images feature vividly colored depictions of the poets seated on tatami mats, affixed to wooden boards. They were created in {{nihongo|1638|寛永15th year }}.
==== Sōja Sanbasō Mask Panels (Two Panels) ==== These two wooden panels depict white and black Sanbasō masks in vivid polychrome, mounted on framed boards. The donor, Kanzaburō Mizukabu, dedicated them in January {{nihongo|1638|寛永15th year }} to commemorate the reconstruction of the main hall.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Excavation Report on Noto Provincial Capital Sites (平成28・29・30th year 度に実施した能登国府確認調査報告)|year=2020|publisher=Nanao City Board of Education|page=6}}</ref>
=== Access === The shrine is accessible from Nanao City and its surrounding historic sites.
=== References === {{reflist}}
=== External Links === * [https://www.ishikawa-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/j1375/ Noto Province General Shrine] – Ishikawa Prefecture Shrine Association {{Shinto shrines}}
